Trends in the Streetwear Aftermarket¶

By Michael Weinberger & Benyam Ephrem


Overview¶

The sneaker & streetwear reselling market is a near 2 billion dollar industry, expecting to triple in the next 5 years.

Individuals spend thousands of dollars a year on pieces of software, private information groups, and more to help secure these sought after items in order to resell for profit, sometimes at even 500% of their original retail price.

How Does This Work?¶

Retailers create artificial scarcity for the products in an effort to increase the hype and desire for them. This augmented desire and demand leads to higher prices, more publicity, and subsequently maximal profit.

There are 3 key interactors in this system:

1. Suppliers¶
2. Resellers¶
3. End Consumers¶

Let's look at each of these in more depth.

Suppliers¶

Suppliers are the original makers of a streetwear product. They define authenticity, drive branding, and decide supply of their products.

For most products with reputable brands in this space (i.e. Yeezy, Supreme), the more limited an item is, the more desirable it is.

This leads to a mutual benefit: suppliers profit from selling to resellers, resellers profit from low stock and high demand (due to hype), and end consumers get a scarce product that is now more valuable to possess.

So although an original supplier could sell at the end consumer price, it is more beneficial to the brand to create the artifical scarcity and sell at a (still high and very profitable) retail price.

Resellers¶

Resellers use special software like bots (i.e. AIObot, Prism) to purchase sneakers after they "drop" (release). Often, a normal person cannot buy the most sought after streetwear themselves with a normal web client (browsing to the site and checking out).

Bots that the resellers operate will buy up all of the inventory as soon as the sneakers are open for purchase and supply sells out in seconds.

End Consumers¶

These are the final consumers who purchase the items in the aftermarket). Sites like StockX (which we will be scraping our data from for analysis) give these consumers a place to purchase these items.

StockX strives to be a transparent market where consumers can see extensive final resale prices for the products that they want to buy. People can make bids, place immediate buys, or become a seller themselves.

Why It All Works¶

At each level of product exchange, the prices get higher and profits are consistently made.

The key fact that makes it all come together is that each level gets more value, not less.

Our Investigation & Analysis¶

With such an incredibly interesting micro-economy and marketplace, there exist fascinating trends that we can analyze to better understand how buyers & sellers are interacting.

We decided to look at 3 popular brands, Nike, Supreme, and Kith.

For each brand we will ask what features of a product (category, color, retail price, etc.) best correlate with resale price.

In other words, can we use these predictors to recommend to each of these brands what future products they should work on to maximize hype and resale price.

We will be sourcing our data from StockX given that it is the largest online marketplace for buying and selling sneakers & streetware.

StockX offers a public API, but we will be directly consuming the API that their web client consumes by reproducing requests ourselves.

Data Collection¶

The first step in the process is to collect all of the data that we need. To do this, we will be scraping StockX.

While StockX does have a public facing API with documentation, it is relatively weak and unsupported. We had to find a way to get data on thousands of products all at once. To do this, we snooped the requests being made by the browser via the Chrome network tab when you search for a product on the StockX.

We duplicated the headers and URL and luckily, StockX presented us with very robust and exhaustive data on all of the returned products.


Something we unfortunately realized is that StockX will only return you a maximum of 1000 products, no matter what the search query is. To somewhat remedy this, we decided to add filters and perform multiple searches. So, instead of searching all categories for Nike, Kith, and Supreme, we searched an array of categories for each one and concatenated the results. This gave us around 1,500 products for each brand.

Another issue we ran into is that because we are not using the supported public endpoints, the StockX API will rate limit your IP if you try to query it too much. In order to get around this, we made use of around 100 proxies that we randomly rotated through to bypass this security measure. With this, we were able to successfully query the StockX API and scrape the data we needed.

# list of brands to query
brands = ['nike', 'kith', 'supreme']
categories = ['sneakers', 'streetwear', 'collectibles']

# raw data dictionary to be used later
raw_data = {}

'''
Utility function to get 
a random proxy for our query
'''
def get_random_proxy():
  raw_proxy_index = random.randint(0, len(proxies) - 1)
  raw_proxy = proxies[raw_proxy_index]
  raw_proxy_fields = raw_proxy.split(':')

  proxy = f'{raw_proxy_fields[2]}:{raw_proxy_fields[3]}@{raw_proxy_fields[0]}:{raw_proxy_fields[1]}'
  proxy_dict = {"http": f'http://{proxy}', "https": f'https://{proxy}'}

  return proxy_dict

'''
Get number of pages for a given
search query via StockX website
'''
def get_num_pages(brand, category):
  response = requests.get(
      f'{stockx_api}/browse?productCategory={category}&sort=most-active&_search={brand}&dataType=product&country=US',
      headers=stockx_headers,
      proxies=get_random_proxy()
  )

  if response.status_code != 200:
    raise Exception('Blocked by StockX') 

  body = response.json()
  pagination = body['Pagination']
  last_page_url = pagination['lastPage']
  last_page_index = last_page_url.index('page=')
  last_page = int(last_page_url[last_page_index + 5:])

  return last_page

'''
Get product data given a page
and a search query (a brand in our case)
'''
def get_products(brand, category, page):
  response = requests.get(
      f'{stockx_api}/browse?productCategory={category}&sort=most-active&_search={brand}&dataType=product&country=US&page={page}',
      headers=stockx_headers,
      proxies=get_random_proxy()
  )

  if response.status_code != 200:
    raise Exception('Blocked by StockX') 

  body = response.json()
  products = body['Products']

  return products

'''
Main function to concatenate products
queried for each page for each brand
and store in our raw_data map
'''
def get_brand_data(brand):
  products = []

  for category in categories:
    num_pages = get_num_pages(brand, category)

    for page in range(num_pages):
      products += get_products(brand, category, page)

  raw_data[brand] = products

for brand in brands:
  get_brand_data(brand)

Data Processing¶

The StockX API returns their responses in JSON, which makes it relatively easy for us to do some basic cleaning and load it into a Pandas DataFrame.

However, there was a nested JSON object in the response that we had to manually pull values from. Another big issue we had to deal with was the color of each product. Each product on StockX has a colorway, which is the variant of the product. This colorway is not necessarily a normal color, like black, but could be something like "dark obsidian." To remedy this, we created a mapping from unknown colorway to a known color by manually looking at each product (there was only around 50 unknown colorways that we had to manually map).

nike_products = raw_data['nike']

'''
Utility function to grab the market
object field and tack on the values
we care about
'''
def add_market_data(row):
  market_data = row['market']

  row['totalDollars'] = market_data['totalDollars']
  row['salesThisPeriod'] = market_data['salesThisPeriod']
  row['annualHigh'] = market_data['annualHigh']
  row['annualLow'] = market_data['annualLow']
  row['lowestAsk'] = market_data['lowestAsk']
  row['averageDeadstockPrice'] = market_data['averageDeadstockPrice']

  # Retail Premium
  if row['averageDeadstockPrice'] is not None:
    diff = row['averageDeadstockPrice'] - row['retailPrice']
    row['percent_over_retail'] = diff / row['retailPrice']

  return row

def extract_color(row):
  raw_colorway = row['colorway'] if row['colorway'] else 'black'
  colorway = raw_colorway.lower()
  extracted_color = None

  for color in colors:
    if color in colorway:
      extracted_color = color
      break

  if colorway in unknown_color_mapping and extracted_color is not None:
    extracted_color = unknown_color_mapping[colorway]

  extracted_color = extracted_color if extracted_color is not None else 'black'
  
  row['color'] = extracted_color

  return row


'''
Utility function to take in array of product
data scraped from StockX, load into a dataframe,
and grab our desired values
'''
def prune_brand_data(raw_brand_data):
  # Create dataframe
  df_raw = pd.DataFrame(raw_brand_data)

  # Convert type of retailPrice
  df_raw['retailPrice'] = pd.to_numeric(df_raw['retailPrice'])

  # Populate nested market data
  df_raw = df_raw.apply(lambda row: add_market_data(row), axis=1)

  # Grab the columns that we will be working with
  df = df_raw[[
    'category', 'colorway', 'gender', 'productCategory',
    'releaseDate', 'retailPrice', 'totalDollars', 'salesThisPeriod',
    'annualHigh', 'annualLow', 'lowestAsk', 'averageDeadstockPrice', 'percent_over_retail', '_tags']]

  # Extract color
  df = df.apply(lambda row: extract_color(row), axis=1)

  # Filter critical fields for empty states
  df = df.replace(to_replace='None', value=np.nan)
  df = df[df['retailPrice'].notnull()]
  df = df[df['averageDeadstockPrice'].notnull()]
  df = df[df['percent_over_retail'].notnull()]

  return df

nike_df = prune_brand_data(nike_products)
kith_df = prune_brand_data(kith_products)
supreme_df = prune_brand_data(supreme_products)

Exploratory Analysis¶

After processing and preparing the data, the first thing we wanted to do was to generally analyze it.

Investigating Average Resale Profits¶

What are the average resell profits for each of the brands?

In [4]:
'''
Exploratory Analysis
'''

# Compute the average resell margin for the brands

def compute_average_resell_margin(brand):
  if brand == 'nike':
    df = nike_df
  elif brand == 'kith':
    df = kith_df
  else:
    df = supreme_df

  df['resell_margin'] = df.apply(
      lambda row: float(row['averageDeadstockPrice']) - float(row['retailPrice']),
      axis=1
  )
  df['resell_margin_total'] = df.apply(
      lambda row: float(row['resell_margin']) * float(row['salesThisPeriod']),
      axis=1
  )

  total_margins = df["resell_margin_total"].sum()
  num_sales = df["salesThisPeriod"].sum()

  return round(total_margins / num_sales, 2)

for brand in brands:
  print(f'{brand} average resale profit ${compute_average_resell_margin(brand)}')

So this is interesting, these heatmaps show us something that might have been subtle before. Products can have margins below 0, a loss.

This can happen when a product is over-hyped and the release does not go well. Or, the product may just not be that desirable and it is no longer a good item to even bring to the resale market if you bought it at retail (you will lose money trying to resell it, but may be fine if you want to cut your losses short on massive inventory).

Supreme¶

We notice that their highest margin products also reside in the streetwear category, with brown, pink, and yellow toned products seeing high margins.

Nike¶

Nike's highest volume category was sneakers. We see that Navy sneakers reap the highest margins. But the mean resale margin for Navy sneakers seems a bit high, we need to be cautious of outliers here. We will take note of this as we continue.

We also see that Nike does not offer collectibles in that many colors which makes sense as Nike has very low relative sales volume coming from their collectibles.

Kith¶

Next, Kith has a wide variety of colors performing evenly well in streetwear. In sneakers, Gold and multi-color sneakers have high relative margins.

Again, we should be wary of outliers and "one-off" products skewing the data. In collectibles we see solid resale margins hovering around \$40, above that of the streetwear which sits around \$25.

This brings us into the next point. Up until now, we have only been looking at raw profit margin. However, we should also be considering the price premium of the product, which is the profit margin relative to the retail price of the product.

Do Higher Retail Prices Equate To Higher Resale Premuims?¶

It is common for profit margins to increase the more expensive a product is. This is because the more it costs to produce a product, the more risk the creater takes on before sale.

So is this the case with these scare products in the streetwear market? We predict that there may be some counterintuitive results because much of the margins are artifically manipulated.

A commodity has no hype and will likely have clear margin increases as the cost of unit production increases. On the other hand, in the space we are looking at, collectibles as cheap as \$50 having resales of \$800 (\$750 gross profit) and sneakers that cost $220 can resale at \$300 (\$80, a lower gross profit).

Let's see:

In [0]:

For Supreme, it seems like sales are centered over relatively cheaper products (= \$50) with relatively lower premiums of around = 20% to = 50%.

For Nike, though, we something very interesting. Sales volume is concentrated around products between \$150 - \$200, which makes sense as this is the range for which their sneakers are priced. However, what we see is that most Nike products are being sold under retail.

For Kith, we see something very similar to Supreme, the product's retail prices are focused on reliatvely cheaper products (= \$50) with price premiums of = 15% to = 50%.

Now what?

Now that we have explored correlations between features we could extract from the StockX data, let's go further.

Can we find a way to look at these relationships and establish connections? This may or may not be possible with the data that we have collected.

Can we build a model matching features we have analyzed, such as category, color, demographic, and retail price to the price premium of a product. What this would effectively do is build us a model for predicting a product's "hype."

Machine Learning¶

Before we start doing some linear regressions and ML, we are going to want to organize the data just a bit more. We have 3 categorical features that we want to convert to numerical.

In [37]:
categories = ['sneakers', 'streetwear', 'collectibles']
genders = ['men', 'women', 'child', 'preschool', 'toddler', 'unisex']
colors = [
  'black', 'white', 'blue', 'red', 'gold', 'orange',
  'navy', 'yellow', 'gray', 'silver',
  'purple', 'green', 'brown', 'pink'
]

# Convert the categorical variables to numerical
def convert_categorical_data(df):
  features = ['retailPrice']

  for category in categories:
    col_name = 'is_' + category
    df[col_name] = df.apply(lambda row: 1 if row['productCategory'] == category else 0, axis=1)
    features.append(col_name)

  for gender in genders:
    col_name = 'is_' + gender
    df[col_name] = df.apply(lambda row: 1 if row['gender'] == gender else 0, axis=1)
    features.append(col_name)

  for color in colors:
    col_name = 'is_' + color
    df[col_name] = df.apply(lambda row: 1 if row['color'] == color else 0, axis=1)
    features.append(col_name)

  return (df, features)

def run_regression(df):
  # Prepare the dataframe
  df_converted, features = convert_categorical_data(df)

  # Extract the feature matrix
  feature_matrix = df_converted[features]

  # Extract the target vector we will predict against
  target_vector = df_converted[['percent_over_retail']]

  # Split test data
  X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(feature_matrix, target_vector, test_size=0.2)

  # Run regression
  linear_model = LinearRegression()
  model = linear_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
  coeff_of_det = model.score(X_test, y_test)

  predictions = linear_model.predict(X_test)

  return (model.coef_, coeff_of_det, predictions, y_test)

# Run the regression and extract coefficients & a prediction vector
coefficients, coeff_of_det, predictions, y_test = run_regression(supreme_df)
print(f"Coefficients: {coefficients}")
print(f"Coefficient of determination: {coeff_of_det}")

So after running our linear model we see that our coefficient of determination hovers around 0 (ranging from -1% to 15%).

The coefficient of determination (denoted R² or r²) is the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable (retail premium percent) that is explained by the independent variables (our features).

An R² value of 0 means that the retail premium cannot be predicted from our feature set.

So instead of trying to create a linear regression, let's create a non-linear model instead. We must be careful to avoid underfitting and overfitting our data, so we must ensure that we pick the appropriate degree of polynomial approximation.

In [84]:
def poly_model(df, company):
  colors = ['black', 'teal', 'yellowgreen', 'gold']

  df_sorted = df.sort_values(by=['retailPrice'])

  feature_matrix = df_sorted[['retailPrice']]
  target_vector = df_sorted[['percent_over_retail']]

  for index, degree in enumerate([2]):
    # Create model
    model = SVR(C=1, degree=degree, epsilon=.02)
    model.fit(feature_matrix, target_vector)
    y_predicted = model.predict(feature_matrix)

    merged_dataset = feature_matrix
    merged_dataset['percent_over_retail'] = y_predicted

    # Plot data points
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    sns.scatterplot(x="retailPrice", y="percent_over_retail", data=df).set_title(f"{company} Retail Price vs. Resale Premium Percent")

    # Draw Regression
    sns.regplot(x="retailPrice", y="percent_over_retail", data=merged_dataset, order=degree, ci=None, truncate=True, color='Black')

poly_model(nike_df, "Supreme")
poly_model(nike_df, "Nike")
poly_model(nike_df, "Kith")

Where Should These Brands Focus Their 2020 Efforts?¶

Ignoring the outliers for the 3 brands, there is definitely a negative relationship between retail price and the price premium. What we learn from this is that products that are relatively cheaper correlate with higher resell margins.
